<Base
  title="colophon · Cyrus Hadavi"
  description="How this site is built, and why it looks the way it does: terminal typography, Persian turquoise, and a verse from Ferdowsi."
>
  <p class="breadcrumb"><a href="/">~</a>/colophon</p>
  <h1 class="page-title">colophon</h1>

  <article class="prose">
    <p>
      This site is two things I grew up with layered on top of each
      other: a terminal, and Persian design.
    </p>

    <h2>the colors</h2>
    <p>
      The accent is <em>firouzeh</em>, Persian turquoise, the stone and
      the color you see on domes and tilework across Iran. The warm
      gold is saffron, used the way you would use actual saffron:
      sparingly, where it counts. They sit on a warm charcoal instead
      of terminal black, and on parchment in the light theme.
    </p>

    <h2>the star</h2>
    <p>
      The eight pointed star in the favicon and section marks is a
      <em>khatam</em> motif, two overlapping squares, the basic unit of
      Persian geometric patternwork. The faint lattice behind the
      homepage hero is the same star, tiled.
    </p>

    <h2>the verse</h2>
    <p>
      The footer carries a line from Ferdowsi's Shahnameh, the epic
      that also named <a href="/work/rakhsh/">Rakhsh</a>:
      <span lang="fa" dir="rtl">توانا بود هر که دانا بود</span>,
      "capable is the one who is wise." A thousand year old comment
      about the relationship between knowledge and ability, on a site
      about systems that are honest about what they know.
    </p>

    <h2>the name</h2>
    <p>
      Cyrus is <span lang="fa" dir="rtl">کوروس</span>, Kuros, in
      Persian. That is where kuros.io comes from.
    </p>

    <h2>the stack</h2>
    <p>
      Astro, static output, content collections for the case studies
      and notes. JetBrains Mono for anything structural, system sans
      for prose, Vazirmatn for Farsi. No frameworks on the client, no
      trackers, no analytics. The heaviest thing on any page is the
      evidence: the demo videos, which only load if you press play.
    </p>
    <p>
      Built and tested with a Node test suite that checks the built
      HTML, because a site that argues for showing your evidence
      should have receipts too. Source lives on
      <a href="https://github.com/cyrushadavi1">GitHub</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
